ary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gerard III Berthout was born about 1165, his father, Gerard II Van Berthout Heer van Grimbergen, was 17 and his mother, Mathilde van Ninove, was 29. He had at least 2 sons with Adélaïde de Rosoy. He died on 2 January 1200, at the age of 36."},"et":{"ABT 1165–02 JAN 1200":"umbes 1165–2. jaanuar 1200","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1167–1212":"1167–1212","1171–1211":"1171–1211","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1195–1253":"1195–1253","1149–1188":"1149–1188","1137–1190":"1137–1190","1190":"1190","1253":"1253","1165":"1165","1195":"1195","1171":"1171","02 JAN 1200":"2. jaanuar 1200","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","1225":"1225","ABT 1165":"umbes 1165","circa 1195":"umbes 1195","1212":"1212","1211":"1211","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188